    "summary": "The Early Bronze Age in Britain, approximately 2500–2000 BC, marks a profound transformation in British prehistory characterised by the widespread adoption of bronze metalworking, the shift from communal megalithic burial to individual inhumation in round barrows, a significant genetic population replacement associated with [[event:1755|Bell Beaker people]] arriving from continental Europe, and the continuation of major monumental construction including the final phases of [[event:43|Stonehenge]].\n\nAncient DNA evidence has demonstrated that the transition to the Early Bronze Age in Britain was accompanied by a dramatic population change: within a few centuries of the Bell Beaker arrival around 2450 BC, the ancestry of individuals buried with Bell Beaker grave goods was largely derived from continental European migrants with steppe-related ancestry, suggesting that the incoming population substantially replaced the earlier Neolithic farming population. This represents one of the most significant demographic events in British prehistoric history.\n\nThe round barrows — earthen burial mounds covering individual graves — that dot the British landscape in their thousands are the most visible legacy of the Early Bronze Age. The individuals buried under these mounds were often accompanied by bronze daggers, pottery, amber and gold ornaments, and other prestige goods that reflect the warrior-aristocratic values of the era. Sites such as Bush Barrow near Stonehenge, with its exceptional gold and bronze grave goods, provide evidence for high-status individuals whose authority was expressed through the control of precious materials and the ability to commission elaborate burial monuments.",
